{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|ic}} – two pieces of meat ({{zh-l|*肉}}). In the bronze script, {{zh-l|*肉}} was corrupted into {{zh-l|*夕}} due to visual similarity. The form with {{zh-l|*夕}} was inherited in later scripts.

{{zh-ref|Chi (2010)}} suggests that meat is scarce in ancient times, so two pieces of meat is a lot, citing a passage from ''{{w|Mencius (book)|Mencius}}'':
: {{zh-x|七十 者 可以 食 肉 矣。|Persons of seventy years may eat meat.|collapsed=y}}

Chang Ping-chuan suggests that it is the duplicative nature of the character that gives the meaning of "many", just like in {{zh-l|*林|forest}}, from {{zh-l|*木|tree; wood}}.

